                    <span class='contribution-person-name'><a href="http://localhost:3000/user/jason-segedy" title="Jason Segedy">Jason Segedy</a></span>
                    <p>When I think of America today, the resulting emotions are inextricably tangled, jumbled, and contradictory. There is a yin and a yang fluctuating through my thoughts: idealism/cynicism; pragmatism/utopianism; greed/generosity; selfishness/altruism; fear/hope; apathy/engagement; cowardice/courage; decadence/virtue.</p><p>Yes, every nation and every culture throughout recorded history has undoubtedly experienced and struggled with these same dichotomies; the same push-and-pull of contrary forces and impulses. But when I think about where we are today in this country, I can't escape the feeling that we are at a real crossroads; a true tipping-point where what we decide to do right here, right now, will affect the future in a deep and profound way.</p><p>We have a cultural, economic, and social identity crisis in this country. We are facing challenges in all of these realms that have transcended the ability of our existing institutions to deal with them. Our political, economic, cultural, and religious institutions are dysfunctional and broken, and they are simply not up to the task.</p><p>There is a season and a time to every purpose. If you believe Neil Howe and William Strauss (I do), we are in the beginning stages of a once every 80-odd-years-or-so realignment of our society that is cyclical and generational. The change is inevitable, but the shape that it will take is not. There is great opportunity and great danger ahead.</p><p>I won't bore everyone with a litany of what I think went wrong in this country or what I think should change. What most of us could probably agree on is that SOME sort of change is needed. Things cannot (and will not) continue on as they have forever. Our trajectory is unsustainable, and it will change when it truly cannot go on as it has.</p><p>My generation (and most of the participants on this site) have really never known deprivation of any of our physical or material needs (food, clothing, shelter, safety); indeed most of us have had the good fortune to enjoy an abundance of these things. But I would argue that we have known great cultural and spiritual deprivation (unity-of-purpose, social ties-that-bind, objective truth, and inner peace). Our individualism, utlitarianism, naturalism, and materialism has had its benefits, but it has not been without its liabilites.</p><p>So, in closing, and back to the yin and the yang -- I believe that the challenge that we are all faced with, when boiled down to its very essence, is this: to collectively recapture the balance between the individual and the society; between people and things; and individually, between the physical and spiritual; and between knowledge and wisdom. If we can do that, I am confident that we can navigate any challenge. If we cannot, we will continue, irrevocably to drift into anomie, and some other culture or civilization, unrecognizable to us, will take our place. The choice is ours.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>
