                        <span class='contribution-person-name'><a href="http://localhost:3000/user/jason-segedy" title="Jason Segedy">Jason Segedy</a></span>
                        <p>David, you are right. We (and it is the "Royal We", because although I am speaking about us as a cultural whole, I can and will count myself amongst the chief offenders) don't appreciate personal sacrifice. We don't want it, we don't seek it, and we can't imagine that there is anything to be gained by it. And it is certainly not in the best interest of Wall Street, Madison Avenue, Hollywood, Washington, D.C., or (sadly and infuriatingly) our religious institutions to broach the topic. Personal sacrifice is the last thing that they want us to think about. They want us to buy s**t that we don't need, they want our money in the collection plate, and they want us to view politics as an infotainment reality TV show, not as something that involves public policy and personal responsibility.</p><p>We have yet to go through the crucible and come out on the other side: whether transformed, or found wanting. But we will. It is inevitable.</p><p>We live in accordance with this credo:</p><p>"Self-sacrifice? But it is precisely the self that cannot and must not be sacrificed." - Ayn Rand</p><p>Not this one:</p><p>"Whoever wants to be a leader among you must be your servant, and whoever wants to be first among you must be the slave of everyone else." - Jesus Christ</p><p>Or even this one:</p><p>"It's only after we've lost everything that we're free to do anything." -Tyler Durden, Fight Club</p><p>I bet you never thought you'd see those two quotes together. . .</p><p>I have yet to hear a story of personal greatness or social transformation that didn't involve deep and profound sacrifice. &nbsp;Being part of the problem myself, I don't have the answers to our problems, but we (the rich, the poor, the secular, the religious, and, most certainly, myself) could profit from considering the following:</p><p>"If I. . .can fathom all mysteries and all knowledge, and if I have a faith that can move mountains, but do not have love, I am nothing." - Paul the Apostle</p><p>Treating each other as valued brothers and sisters, rather than as enemies, or objects, or consumers, or votes, would be a wonderful first step toward true national greatness.</p>
