                <p>Scenes from the 2004 election capture, for me, both what unites us and what divides us.&nbsp; That election season, for the first time since the McGovern campaign I was directly involved in campaigning.&nbsp; I spent the months before the election phoning and knocking on the doors of people likely to vote for John Kerry.&nbsp; On Election Day I worked the polls.<br /><br />When I arrived at the polls, the George Bush supporters had already set up camp.&nbsp; We parked ourselves across the driveway from them.&nbsp; Throughout the cold wet day we chatted with each other across the driveway.&nbsp; We took turns running to the convenience store across the street to bring back coffee and hot chocolate for each other, to keep a bit of the chill away.&nbsp; By the end of the day, when voters weren&rsquo;t coming up the drive we mostly chatted together on one side or the other of the drive &ndash; taking turns on the Bush or Kerry side, then scurrying back apart to grab our respective signs when a car approached in case the voter passing by was undecided.&nbsp; <br /><br />At one point, a Bush supporter complained to the election workers that the Kerry workers were inside the flags.&nbsp; The election workers came out and told my spouse and me to move outside of the flags &ndash; without saying a word to the Bush team directly across from us, also inside the flags, and the folks who had actually counted off the distance (some 300&rsquo; inside the flags the election workers had improperly placed 400&rsquo; from the polling place).<br /><br />All of us moved our camps outside the flags, even though the Bush supporters had not been threatened with arrest, or even asked to move.&nbsp; A few hours later the issue was resolved and we helped each other move everything back to our original locations.<br /><br />Anyone watching us through the day would have guessed we were old and dear friends, rather than strangers thrown together for a day because we held opposite political views.<br /><br />In sharp contrast, near the end of the day a voter passed by and glared at our Kerry sign without speaking.&nbsp; He drove off and returned a few minutes later with a truck filled with large signs bearing graphic abortion images, which he insisted on sticking in our faces while he called us baby killers.&nbsp; From the other side of the political spectrum, the day after election (which yielded not only a Kerry loss, but the passage of Ohio&rsquo;s marriage discrimination amendment) a whisper campaign began among Kerry supporters, despondent over the Bush win, that the election had been lost because &ldquo;those gays&rdquo; couldn&rsquo;t wait patiently until after this crucial election for their turn at the civil rights table.&nbsp; "Those gays;" many of whom had made the Solomon-like decision to devote our limited resources trying to get Kerry elected rather than on defeating the constitutional amendment aimed direcly at our families.<br /><br />We are at our worst when we see ourselves as &ldquo;us,&rdquo; and whoever makes a convenient target to blame the world&rsquo;s ills on as &ldquo;them.&rdquo;<br /><br />We are at our best when we sit at the table with each other, learn each others&rsquo; stories, come to care for one another, and discover that our differences are just part of what makes life interesting and, in the end, discover that that perhaps we aren&rsquo;t that different after all.</p>
